<div id="review_751735404" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/751735404" />
    <a title="Jane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21651564-jane"><img alt="Jane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442492646p2/21651564.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/751735404?book_show_action=true">Oct 28, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jane" href="/user/show/21651564-jane">Jane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21651564-jane?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21651564-jane?shelf=childrens-books">childrens-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21651564-jane?shelf=49-or-less-pages">49-or-less-pages</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer751735404" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer552739457079650749">The classroom where I teach has a copy of this book as part of the classroom collection; this opinion is my honest opinion.<br/><br/>As a preschool teacher I have used the Pigeon book series by Mo Williams on a daily basis. One day my teacher&apos;s aid was absent and the children requested for the substitute to read <i>The Pigeon Wants a Puppy</i> and she read it in a monotone, showing no enthusiasms for what she was reading, nor did she try to draw comments and interaction from the children. My class of children th</span>
  <span id="freeText552739457079650749" style="display:none">The classroom where I teach has a copy of this book as part of the classroom collection; this opinion is my honest opinion.<br /><br />As a preschool teacher I have used the Pigeon book series by Mo Williams on a daily basis. One day my teacher's aid was absent and the children requested for the substitute to read <i>The Pigeon Wants a Puppy</i> and she read it in a monotone, showing no enthusiasms for what she was reading, nor did she try to draw comments and interaction from the children. My class of children then explained the story to her and told he she didn't read it right. That being said, if preschool age children don't enjoy a book with the potential to teach lessons about wanting things that are not good for them, being selfish and getting along with others using excellent books like <i>The Pigeon Wants a Puppy</i>, it is the fault of the reader if the child misses this book's message and the fun of reading it. (One thing I found was that the youngest preschool children had no idea what a walrus was, so I printed several pictures from the Internet to help explain a new word and animal to them.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="552739457079650749" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


